TikTok hides unpleasant videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
Take a look at China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok has censored videos mentioning Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian said.
According to the documents, the owner of TikTok (ByteDance) uses the app to promote China’s foreign policy goals abroad.
Most of the violations related to China’s policy fall under the “incitement of hatred.”
In each case, TikTok places unpleasant posts in a context appropriate to the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not appear to be censorship.
For example, a ban on criticism of China’s socialist system falls under a general ban on “criticism or attacks on the politics and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or genocide in Cambodia falls under “the distortion of the history of China or other countries.”
The document also lists the banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen" of Vido Preko, including North Korean leaders Kim Jong-un, Kim Jong-un and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, and the presidents of the United States.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, as stated in the document.
Posts from the first category are deleted by social network administrators and may result in a user being blocked.
Not too severe violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applicable: “We are now using a localized approach for moderation, as well as attracting independent local specialists.”
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says the co-founder of the "Producer Center" Rustem Bogdanov.
“Producer Center” is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All promotional materials of bloggers "Producer Center" agrees with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without consent, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether TikTok can talk about politics or Putin, Bogdanov says he has seen such publications.
Roman Zaripov, founder of Our Didgital, agrees with Bogdanov: "The basic rules for users TikTok lists in the user agreement: you can not post shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on."
But under these rules, you can summarize any content that moderators do not like, notes Zaripov.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian TikTok partner.
According to TikTok, the number of its users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
According to the user agreement, only people over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
Administrators of the social network check their age with artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019 ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of the WeWork coworking.
